This paper deals with non-monotonic reasoning in description logics, which is a topic that falls under the intersection of several sub-fields in computer science. The most likely category is cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), as non-monotonic reasoning is a fundamental concept in AI and the paper proposes an extension to an existing non-monotonic description logic. The paper also discusses the complexity of reasoning tasks, which is a common theme in cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). Additionally, the paper deals with knowledge representation and databases, which are relevant to cs.DB (Databases). The paper also mentions preferential semantics, which is a concept in natural language processing and computational linguistics, falling under cs.CL (Computation and Language). Finally, the paper discusses the problem of property blocking inheritance, which is a topic in computational reasoning and could fall under cs.CR (Computational Complexity).
